If you want to stick to a routine, start your day with your workout.

Force yourself to wake up and go for 3 weeks. Create the habit. Go straight to bed and don’t waste time binge watching Netflix. Lay your gym clothes out the night prior. Just go.

It’s been 17 years today since my Dad passed away.

A loyal man who worked the same job for 27 years until a stroke caused by diabetes knocked him out of it, my Dad would drive two hours each way per day to be home in time to coach little league.

I dedicated my life to being a better father than my father was and to work to help people not die from unhealthy choices and obesity. 

I hope that he is looking down at my family right now smiling and it’s a travesty that he never got a chance to meet his Grandkids. 

I’ll never forget when we won the Little League championship and we cracked open non-alcoholic champaign and in his excitement he screamed out “We’re number one!” and his dentures flew out of his mouth. 😂

I’ll never forget when I wanted to be a professional baseball player and he’d get home from work, sweaty and tired because his car didn’t have air conditioning, and would stay out there until I was content, sometimes hours.

It’s not about how long you live, but about what you do while on this earth.

I started training in 1993 and haven’t missed a workout since.

-I trained the day after my 2 knee surgeries. 
-I trained the day of my abdominal diastasis surgery, although it was only cardio. 

The fact of the matter is that I love training and I eat to support my goals. While there are other variables, my love of training is what got me here.

And we still have a lot of room to improve!

Modern farming practices can sometimes impact the nutritional content of food in several ways:

	1.	Soil Depletion: Intensive farming can lead to soil nutrient depletion. When crops are repeatedly grown on the same land, the soil loses minerals, vitamins, and microbes faster than they can be replenished. This can result in crops that are less nutritious.
	2.	Selective Breeding and Genetic Modification: Crops have been genetically modified and selectively bred to increase yield, improve disease resistance, and enhance certain desirable traits like size or color. However, this can sometimes lead to a reduction in certain nutrients.
	3.	Fertilizers and Pesticides: The use of synthetic fertilizers and pesticides can affect the natural growth processes of plants. While they increase crop yields, they can also lead to a reduction in the nutritional value of the produce.
	4.	Harvesting Techniques: Modern harvesting techniques often involve picking fruits and vegetables before they are fully ripe. This is done to extend their shelf life but can result in lower nutrient levels, as many crops reach their full nutritional value only when fully ripened on the plant.
	5.	Food Processing and Storage: Processing methods like canning, freezing, and drying, as well as long storage periods, can lead to nutrient loss in food products.
	6.	Monoculture Farming: This practice involves growing a single type of crop over a large area for many years. It can lead to a decrease in soil quality and biodiversity, which in turn can affect the nutritional content of crops.

While these practices are effective in increasing food production, they can sometimes compromise the nutritional quality of the food. It’s important to balance the need for quantity with quality in food production.
